properties.Title: Flood Warning Being Issued For The Red River At St. Adolphe
properties.Summary:
Description: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a Flood Warning on the Red River at St. Adolphe due to operation of the Red River Floodway. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions given by local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-10-13T15:30:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2019-10-12T15:35:36-05:00, 2FFE3383-A936-7A05-F2AD-D5348079BC4F
Area: The Red River at St. Adolphe
properties.Author: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization

properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect. First heavy flurries of the season tonight. Flurries, at times heavy, will develop off Lake Superior tonight. While snowfall accumulations are not forecast to be particularly heavy due to temperatures hovering near zero, significantly reduced visibilities in snow can be expected at times. Motorists travelling along portions of Highway 17 between Thunder Bay and Wawa are advised to watch for quickly changing weather conditions and adjust their driving accordingly. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: As of early this morning much of southern Manitoba remains under a winter storm warning as a massive low pressure system continues to relentlessly pummel the area with heavy snow and strong winds. Widespread snowfall accumulations of 40-60 cm have been reported in much of western Manitoba and the western Red River Valley and many highways remain closed. Widespread power outages continue to plague the region with significant numbers of downed or damaged trees. The low pressure system will remain more or less stationary and hence snowfall and strong winds will continue, with further accumulations ranging from 5 to 15 cm over the course of the day. The snow will continue to be accompanied by winds gusting as high as 60 km/h giving near-zero visibility at times in blowing snow. Travelling will remain difficult if not impossible today as the heavy accumulating snow, strong winds, and temperatures near zero will result in treacherous conditions. Further downed trees and power outages are to be expected. The storm will begin to weaken tonight, although a few areas will still see another 5 cm or so accumulation by Sunday morning. The winter storm warning has been ended for Winnipeg as the worst of the system has now pushed west of the city. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: As of late this morning the western Parklands and Interlake remain under a winter storm warning as a massive low pressure system continues to relentlessly pummel the area with heavy snow and strong winds. The low pressure system will remain more or less stationary and hence snowfall and strong winds will continue, with further accumulations ranging from 5 to 15 cm over the course of the day. The snow will continue to be accompanied by winds gusting as high as 60 km/h giving near-zero visibility at times in blowing snow. Elsewhere, widespread snowfall accumulations of 40-60 cm have been reported in much of western Manitoba and the western Red River Valley and many highways remain closed. Widespread power outages continue to plague the region with significant numbers of downed or damaged trees. However, accumulating snowfall has now ended for the entire Red River Valley and areas westward to Brandon. Travelling will remain difficult if not impossible today as the heavy accumulating snow, strong winds, and temperatures near zero will result in treacherous conditions. Further downed trees and power outages are to be expected. The storm will begin to weaken tonight, although a few areas will still see another 5 cm or so accumulation by Sunday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-13T01:59:54-00:00

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. An approaching low pressure system is expected to bring strong winds and blizzard conditions to Resolute beginning Sunday morning and continuing until late in the day on Monday. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
